# ── Security annotation ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
nutms: |md
  ### 🔒 "Nothing Up My Sleeve"
  **Security property:** K[n] derivation is a one-way street.
  The designer **cannot** choose K values to embed a backdoor
  because each K is pinned to a universally verifiable mathematical
  constant (cube root of a prime). Any engineer can independently
  reproduce all 64 values:
  python
  import math
  primes = [2,3,5,7,11,13,17,19,23,...]  # first 64 primes
  K = [int((p**(1/3) % 1) * 2**32) for p in primes]
  
  **Contrast:** Dual_EC_DRBG used unexplained curve-point constants
  → NSA backdoor confirmed (Snowden 2013). SHA-256 is immune to this
  attack class precisely because derivation leaves **zero degrees of
  freedom** for the designer to aim at a backdoor-enabling value.
| {
  near: bottom-center
  style.fill: "#fffde7"
  style.border-radius: 8
  style.stroke: "#f9a825"
  style.stroke-width: 2
}
